g.text: This is the initial set of positions
For each operation, create a new node representing it.
A node of MERGE operation have 2 sons,
A node of MODIFY operation have 1 son.
Now a set is represented by a sub-tree, and the operations applied on a position can be
found on its path to the root.
Each node have two attributes, `timestamp` and `value`, indicating the time this operation
happens and how this operation changes the value of a certain set (sub-tree)
When querying the value of a position, we first find, on the second tree, the last (the one with
greatest timestamp) operation. That an assign operation, and we assume that this operation
assign it to `x`, on time `t`. Then we need to query how much we add (by MERGE operation)
It's obvious that only operations with timestamp greater than `t` on the first tree should be
taken into account. This can be done by binary search on Link Cut Tree within O(log n).
